<li class="comment" id="comment-54453">
    <div class="authorpic">
		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/2bae5d2b765215bf205c146764182eed?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=R' class='avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> 
	</div>
    <div class="entry">

        <h3>American Abroad <span class="date">Nov 14th, 2010</span></h3>
        <p>Your experiences with cafe&#8217; latte and cappuccino are because, by and large, milk (latte) is a breakfast beverage, and only for breakfast (however, it is customary for children to have milk at all times of the day).<br />
In the northern, more tourist-y cities (Roma, Milano, Vincenza, etc.), bars accustomed to receiving foreign patrons will, of course, sell what the customers wish to buy.</p>
		<div class="actions">
			<span class="reply"><a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/2007/08/20/an-illustrated-coffee-guide/?replytocom=54453#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-54453", "54453", "respond", "77")'>Reply</a></span>		</div>
        

