<li class="comment" id="comment-52648">
    <div class="authorpic">
		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/5709cae8c0ba297b3157111211d4fa50?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=R' class='avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> 
	</div>
    <div class="entry">

        <h3>elissaf <span class="date">Aug 26th, 2007</span></h3>
        <p>I believe the flat white originated in Australia (although it may be similar to cafe con leche).</p>
<p>The difference between a capp and a flat white isn&#8217;t simply the foam.  The milk is steamed at a much higher temperature in a cappucino, causing the milk protein to stretch causing, as the foam separates, the milk to become watery.  The steamed milk in a flat white warms while retaining its creaminess.  </p>
<p>The cup can be filled to the top with steamed milk (or not), and there will often be a dollop of creamy (not foamy) foam.</p>
		<div class="actions">
			<span class="reply"><a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/2007/08/20/an-illustrated-coffee-guide/?replytocom=52648#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-52648", "52648", "respond", "77")'>Reply</a></span>		</div>
        

    </div>
 
