<li class="comment" id="comment-52879">
    <div class="authorpic">
		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/303b7b5c982be8915adf917f973890f0?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=R' class='avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> 
	</div>
    <div class="entry">

        <h3>duarte <span class="date">Sep 4th, 2007</span></h3>
        <p>And if you go to Portugal for a coffee, like Pedro Couto e Santos suggested, there are some specific names you should use.</p>
<p>BICA [bee-cah] is the best espresso you ever had.<br />
BICA CHEIA [bee-cah shey-ah] is an espresso with extra water.<br />
CAFE DUPLO is a double espresso.<br />
CAFE DUPLO PINGADO [peen gah-do] is a double espresso with a tiny droplet of milk. My favourite!<br />
GALAO [guh-lao] is a glass of coffee with lots of milk.<br />
GALAO ESCURO [guh-lao sjkoo-roh] is a longer shot of coffee in a glass with milk.<br />
GALAO (ESCURO) DA MAQUINA you should ask to be sure they use hot steamed milk.</p>
<p>Only downside in Portuguese coffee is that they use UHT (dead milk). So you are better of asking a glass of water next to your espresso.</p>
<p>Try to look for a place that sells Delta, Buondi or Segafredo coffee.</p>
		<div class="actions">
			<span class="reply"><a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/2007/08/20/an-illustrated-coffee-guide/?replytocom=52879#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-52879", "52879", "respond", "77")'>Reply</a></span>		</div>
        

