<li class="comment" id="comment-53332">
    <div class="authorpic">
		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/8fb4e9b37e19702ee8cd2562a45ebf5d?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=R' class='avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> 
	</div>
    <div class="entry">

        <h3><a href='http://jfmanzo.wordpress.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>John</a> <span class="date">Jan 18th, 2008</span></h3>
        <p>Espresso is NOT made by pushing &#8220;pressurized steam&#8221; through coffee grounds. It is made by pushing hot WATER through a bed of finely ground coffee; the water is &#8220;pushed&#8221; by the actions of a rotary or a vibrational pump or a piston that is pushed using a lever-activated spring. Steam has nothing to do with it aside from steam in the boiler increasing the resting pressure of the water (and providing steam for milk frothing). The work is done by the pump or the piston.</p>
<p>I pity everyone on here who has never had a proper 5- or 6-oz cappuccino made with silky microfoam at a decent cafe.</p>
		<div class="actions">
			<span class="reply"><a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/2007/08/20/an-illustrated-coffee-guide/?replytocom=53332#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-53332", "53332", "respond", "77")'>Reply</a></span>		</div>
        

    </div>
 
</li>

