<li class="comment" id="comment-53826">
    <div class="authorpic">
		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/ee88314a678cbc1b08bfe0530cafdafd?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=R' class='avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> 
	</div>
    <div class="entry">

        <h3>Sam <span class="date">Oct 31st, 2008</span></h3>
        <p>Without reading through all this drivel, nothing about espresso means that the beans have to be roasted dark.  The drawings are nice, but the fundamental concept of what makes espresso is flawed.  One of the reasons espresso is often flavorless and bitter is because places insist on using burnt beans because they don&#8217;t know any better.</p>
<p>As for cuban coffee, all of the traditional cuban style coffee I&#8217;ve had has been made with a moka pot, which discounts it from being an espresso drink.  Many of the cuban places these days use espresso machines for convenience&#8230;but most of the sit down old mom and pop places here in Florida use moka pots.  Mmm&#8230;makes me want a cafe dulce&#8230;</p>
		<div class="actions">
			<span class="reply"><a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='/2007/08/20/an-illustrated-coffee-guide/?replytocom=53826#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-53826", "53826", "respond", "77")'>Reply</a></span>		</div>
        

    </div>
 
